      "snowpackStructure": {
        "comment": "The surface of the snowpack will freeze to form a strong crust only at high altitudes and will soften quickly. In the last few days the natural activity of medium wet and gliding avalanches has gradually increased. The snowpack will be wet all the way through at low and intermediate altitudes. <br/> At higher altitudes, snow cover becomes thinner and patchy; it is better at mid-altitudes, which are less exposed to the wind. <br/> The surface snowpack changes rapidly depending on the aspect and gradient: crusts of various types and thicknesses alternate. In steep terrain there is a danger of falling on the hard crust, especially adjacent to ridgelines and in pass areas. <br/> Weak layers exist in the snowpack in particular on steep shady slopes. <br/> As a consequence of mild temperatures and solar radiation the snowpack settled. These spring-like weather conditions will give rise to increasing consolidation of the snowpack. <br/> Below approximately 1800 m hardly any snow is lying."
      },
